.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Secp256k1 \- Perl interface to libsecp256k1
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Secp256k1;
\&
\&        # first, create a context
\&        my $secp256k1 = Bitcoin::Secp256k1\->new;
\&
\&        # then, use it to perform ECC operations
\&        my $public_key = $secp256k1\->create_public_key($private_key);
\&        my $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message($private_key, $message);
\&        my $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message($public_key, $signature, $message);
\&
\&        # Schnorr signatures are implemented
\&        my $schnorr_signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message_schnorr($private_key, $message);
\&        my $xonly_public_key = $secp256k1\->xonly_public_key($public_key);
\&        my $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message_schnorr($xonly_public_key, $schnorr_signature, $message);
\&
\&        # Recoverable signatures (used in Ethereum)
\&        my $recoverable_signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message_recoverable($private_key, $message);
\&        my $recovered_pubkey = $secp256k1\->recover_public_key_message($recoverable_signature, $message);
\&        my $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message_recoverable($public_key, $recoverable_signature, $message);
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module implements XS routines that allow accessing common elliptic curve
operations on secp256k1 curve using Perl code. It requires
libsecp256k1 <https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1> to be installed on
the system, and will try to detect and install it automatically using
Alien::libsecp256k1.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
Please note that the module does not treat corrupted data (too short or too
long, badly encoded) as valid arguments and will throw an exception if it gets
them in place of public keys, private keys or signatures. Same is true for
undefined values, which will cause the module to print the help message with
function usage. For some functions like "verify_digest" this means that the
function can fail either by returning false or by throwing an exception. This
can be used to distinguish corrupted data (exception is raised) from invalid
data (false is returned).
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
None \- object is a blessed readonly scalar reference with a memory address of a
C structure. As such, it does not contain any attributes accessible directly
from Perl.
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $secp256k1 = Bitcoin::Secp256k1\->new()
.Ve
.PP
Object constructor. All methods in this package require this object to work
properly. It accepts no arguments.
.PP
\fIverify_private_key\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_private_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_private_key($private_key)
.Ve
.PP
Checks whether bytestring \f(CW$private_key\fR is a valid private key. Private key
is valid if its length is exactly \f(CW32\fR and it is below curve order (when
interpreted as a big\-endian integer).
.PP
Some methods in this module may die if their private key is not valid, but
chances of picking an invalid 32\-byte private key at random are extremely slim.
.PP
\fIverify_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_public_key($public_key)
.Ve
.PP
Checks whether bytestring \f(CW$public_key\fR is a valid public key. Some methods in
this module may die if their public key is not valid.
.PP
\fIcreate_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "create_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key = $secp256k1\->create_public_key($private_key)
.Ve
.PP
Creates a public key from a bytestring \f(CW$private_key\fR and returns a bytestring
\&\f(CW$public_key\fR. \f(CW$private_key\fR must have exact length of \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
The public key is always returned in compressed form, use "compress_public_key" to get uncompressed form.
.PP
\fInormalize_signature\fR
.IX Subsection "normalize_signature"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->normalize_signature($signature)
.Ve
.PP
Performs signature normalization of \f(CW$signature\fR, which is in DER encoding (a
bytestring). Returns the normalized signature. Will return the same signature
if it was already in a normalized form.
.PP
Signature normalization is important because of Bitcoin standard rules.
Normally, Bitcoin nodes will filter out transactions with malleable signatures.
Since this is only a standardness rule, this module will let unnormalized
signatures thorough.
.PP
This method lets you both detect whether the signature was malleable and fix it
to avoid a warning if needed.
.PP
\fIcompress_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "compress_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key = $secp256k1\->compress_public_key($public_key, $want_compressed = !!1)
.Ve
.PP
Changes the compression form of bytestring \f(CW$public_key\fR. If
\&\f(CW$want_compressed\fR is a true value (or omitted / undef), method will return
the key in compressed (default) form. If it is a false value, \f(CW$public_key\fR
will be in uncompressed form. It accepts keys in both compressed and
uncompressed forms.
.PP
While both compressed and uncompressed keys will behave the same during
signature verification, they produce different Bitcoin addresses (because
address is a hashed public key).
.PP
\fIsign_message\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message($private_key, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Signs \f(CW$message\fR, which may be a bytestring of any length, with
\&\f(CW$private_key\fR, which must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR. Returns
DER\-encoded \f(CW$signature\fR as a bytestring.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with double SHA256 (known an HASH256 in Bitcoin)
before passing it to signing algorithm (which expects length \f(CW32\fR bytestrings).
.PP
This method always produces normalized, deterministic signatures suitable to
use inside a Bitcoin transaction.
.PP
\fIsign_message_schnorr\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_message_schnorr"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message_schnorr($private_key, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Signs \f(CW$message\fR, which may be a bytestring of any length, with
\&\f(CW$private_key\fR, which must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR. Returns
a Schnorr \f(CW$signature\fR as a bytestring.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with SHA256 before passing it to signing algorithm.
.PP
This signature is not deterministic, since signing with Schnorr uses 32 bytes
of auxiliary randomness as an additional security measure. You can set a fixed
value to be used instead by setting package variable
\&\f(CW$Bitcoin::Secp256k1::FORCED_SCHNORR_AUX_RAND\fR to any bytestring of length
\&\f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIsign_message_recoverable\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_message_recoverable"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_message_recoverable($private_key, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Signs \f(CW$message\fR, which may be a bytestring of any length, with
\&\f(CW$private_key\fR, which must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR. Returns
a hash reference containing the recoverable signature.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with double SHA256 (known an HASH256 in Bitcoin)
before passing it to signing algorithm (which expects length \f(CW32\fR bytestrings).
.PP
The returned hash reference contains:
.ie n .IP """signature"" \- 64 bytes containing r (32 bytes) and s (32 bytes) values" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWsignature\fR \- 64 bytes containing r (32 bytes) and s (32 bytes) values" 4
.IX Item "signature - 64 bytes containing r (32 bytes) and s (32 bytes) values"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP """recovery_id"" \- Integer from 0 to 3 indicating which recovery method to use" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWrecovery_id\fR \- Integer from 0 to 3 indicating which recovery method to use" 4
.IX Item "recovery_id - Integer from 0 to 3 indicating which recovery method to use"
.PD
.PP
Recoverable signatures allow the public key to be recovered from the signature
and message, which is useful for systems like Ethereum where only the signature
is stored in transactions.
.PP
This method always produces deterministic signatures suitable for use in
recoverable signature systems.
.PP
\fIsign_digest\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_digest"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_digest($private_key, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "sign_message", but it does not perform double SHA256 on its input.
Because of that, \f(CW$message_digest\fR must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIsign_digest_schnorr\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_digest_schnorr"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_digest_schnorr($private_key, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "sign_message_schnorr", but it does not perform SHA256 on its input.
While Schnorr allows any length message, this method requires
\&\f(CW$message_digest\fR to be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIsign_digest_recoverable\fR
.IX Subsection "sign_digest_recoverable"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature = $secp256k1\->sign_digest_recoverable($private_key, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "sign_message_recoverable", but it does not perform double SHA256 on its input.
Because of that, \f(CW$message_digest\fR must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
Returns the same hash reference format as "sign_message_recoverable".
.PP
\fIrecover_public_key_digest\fR
.IX Subsection "recover_public_key_digest"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key = $secp256k1\->recover_public_key_digest($recoverable_signature, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Recovers the public key from a recoverable signature and message digest.
Takes a \f(CW$recoverable_signature\fR (hash reference as returned by signing methods) and
\&\f(CW$message_digest\fR (bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR). Returns the recovered
public key in compressed form.
.PP
This is the core functionality that makes recoverable signatures useful \-
it allows determining which public key created a signature without storing
the public key separately.
.PP
\fIrecover_public_key_message\fR
.IX Subsection "recover_public_key_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key = $secp256k1\->recover_public_key_message($recoverable_signature, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "recover_public_key_digest", but performs double SHA256 on \f(CW$message\fR first.
\&\f(CW$message\fR may be a bytestring of any length.
.PP
\fIverify_message\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message($public_key, $signature, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies \f(CW$signature\fR (DER\-encoded, bytestring) of \f(CW$message\fR (bytestring of
any length) against \f(CW$public_key\fR (compressed or uncompressed, bytestring).
Returns true if verification is successful.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with double SHA256 (known an HASH256 in Bitcoin)
before passing it to verification algorithm (which expects length \f(CW32\fR bytestrings).
.PP
Unlike underlying libsecp256k1 function, this method accepts malleable
signatures. It is recommended to perform signature normalization using
"normalize_signature" first and reject malleable signatures explicitly if
that behavior is not desirable.
.PP
\fIverify_message_schnorr\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_message_schnorr"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message_schnorr($xonly_public_key, $signature, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies \f(CW$signature\fR (Schnorr, bytestring) of \f(CW$message\fR (bytestring of any
length) against \f(CW$xonly_public_key\fR (bytestring). Returns true is verification
is successful.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with SHA256 before passing it to verification
algorithm to ensure digest length of 32 bytes. \fBThis is probably not correct
for most use cases\fR, as schnorr message verification uses tagged hashes with
customizable tags (implemented in Bitcoin::Crypto, not in
Bitcoin::Secp256k1). Use "verify_digest_schnorr" with more specific digest
algorithm instead.
.PP
\fIverify_message_recoverable\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_message_recoverable"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_message_recoverable($public_key, $signature, $message)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies a recoverable \f(CW$signature\fR (hash reference as returned by signing methods) of \f(CW$message\fR (bytestring of any length)
against \f(CW$public_key\fR (compressed or uncompressed, bytestring). Returns true
if verification is successful.
.PP
\&\f(CW$message\fR is first hashed with double SHA256 before verification.
.PP
This method works by recovering the public key from the signature and comparing
it to the provided public key.
.PP
\fIverify_digest\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_digest"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_digest($public_key, $signature, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "verify_message", but it does not perform double SHA256 on its input.
Because of that, \f(CW$message_digest\fR must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIverify_digest_schnorr\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_digest_schnorr"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_digest_schnorr($xonly_public_key, $signature, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "verify_message_schnorr", but it does not perform SHA256 on its
input. While Schnorr allows any length message, this method requires
\&\f(CW$message_digest\fR to be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIverify_digest_recoverable\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_digest_recoverable"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $valid = $secp256k1\->verify_digest_recoverable($public_key, $signature, $message_digest)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "verify_message_recoverable", but it does not perform double SHA256 on its input.
Because of that, \f(CW$message_digest\fR must be a bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR.
.PP
\fIxonly_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "xonly_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $xonly_public_key = $secp256k1\->xonly_public_key($public_key)
.Ve
.PP
Returns a xonly form of \f(CW$public_key\fR. This form is used in Taproot.
.PP
\fInegate_private_key\fR
.IX Subsection "negate_private_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $negated_private_key = $secp256k1\->negated_private_key($private_key)
.Ve
.PP
Negates a private key and returns it.
.PP
\fInegate_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "negate_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $negated_public_key = $secp256k1\->negate_public_key($public_key)
.Ve
.PP
Negates a public key and returns it.
.PP
\fIadd_private_key\fR
.IX Subsection "add_private_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $tweaked = $secp256k1\->add_private_key($private_key, $tweak)
.Ve
.PP
Add a \f(CW$tweak\fR (bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR) to \f(CW$private_key\fR (bytestring of
length \f(CW32\fR). The result is a bytestring containing tweaked private key.
.PP
If the arguments or the resulting key are not valid, an exception will be thrown.
.PP
\fIadd_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "add_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $tweaked = $secp256k1\->add_public_key($public_key, $tweak)
.Ve
.PP
Add a \f(CW$tweak\fR (bytestring of length \f(CW32\fR) to \f(CW$public_key\fR (bytestring with
compressed or uncompressed public key). The result is a bytestring containing
tweaked public key in compressed form.
.PP
If the arguments or the resulting key are not valid, an exception will be thrown.
.PP
\fImultiply_private_key\fR
.IX Subsection "multiply_private_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $tweaked = $secp256k1\->multiply_private_key($private_key, $tweak)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "add_private_key", but performs multiplication instead of addition.
.PP
\fImultiply_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "multiply_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $tweaked = $secp256k1\->multiply_public_key($public_key, $tweak)
.Ve
.PP
Same as "add_public_key", but performs multiplication instead of addition.
.PP
\fIcombine_public_keys\fR
.IX Subsection "combine_public_keys"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $combined = $secp256k1\->combine_public_keys(@pubkeys)
.Ve
.PP
Combines \f(CW@pubkeys\fR together, returning a new pubkey.
.PP
If the arguments or the resulting key are not valid, an exception will be thrown.
.SH IMPLEMENTATION
.IX Header "IMPLEMENTATION"
The module consists of two layers:
.IP \(bu 4
High\-level API, which consists of public, stable methods. These methods should
deliver most of the possible use cases for the library, but some paths may not
be covered. All of these methods simply accept and return values without
storing anything inside the object.
.IP \(bu 4
Low\-level API, which is implemented in XS and private. It interacts directly
with libsecp256k1 and is storing some intermediate state (but never the private
key) in a blessed C structure. It covers all of library\*(Aqs functions which are
valuable in Perl\*(Aqs context. Its existence is only significant to the author and
the contributors.
.Sp
Notable exceptions are the constructor "new" and the destructor, which are
also part of the low\-level API, yet public.
.PP
The module also needs a cryptographically\-secure source of pseudo\-randomness to
deliver the highest level of security. It will try to obtain it from CryptX
or Bytes::Random::Secure. If none of these modules is installed, a warning
will be issued every time randomness is requested by the internals. The library
will continue to work as intended, but randomization is a security feature
which protects against some types of attacks. Refer to libsecp256k1
documentation for details.
.SS TODO
.IX Subsection "TODO"
This module currently covers most usage paths of the base libsecp256k1, the
Schnorr module, and the recovery module. It currently does not aim to cover
every usage path, most notably signing variable length messages with Schnorr
(without digesting first).
.SH CAVEATS
.IX Header "CAVEATS"
Documentation of libsecp256k1 recommends keeping secrets on the stack (not the
heap) and erasing them manually after they are no longer used. This is
impossible in Perl, as it gives programmer no control over memory allocation.
This library does not usually clear the secret key memory by overwriting it
with zeros (unless it explicitly copied the secret to a new buffer). If you
need this level of security, you should probably use libsecp256k1 directly in C
code.
